Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

continuing bird since Jan 27. larger than scrub-jay, long tail with squared tip, pot-bellied no-necked appearance, unique stout bill shape somewhat tanager-like--bright cheddar cheese in color, dark olive-gray head and neck with white "ear spot" below eye, reddish orbital ring, olive-gray upper chest with white band above gray breast, then white and bright pinkish belly, distinctive pattern of fine black barring on white outer rectrices, upperparts darker and somewhat iridescent in deep olive-gray except for noticeable coppery cast to uppertail. photos to follow. another observer had the bird as we arrived at 14:45--usual location "midway" along Panther Canyon trail--we had the bird in view over the next 10 mins as it foraged and moved along the south slope and creekbed away from the Comal River. at that point the bird flew higher up on the south slope and we lost it, presumably as it continued moving along a well-defined side canyon coming in from the south. so far as I know the bird was not relocated over the next 2 hours despite efforts by multiple observers.

Very exciting. This was one of my most memorable birds in my young birding days, and now 35 years later, it is still just as exciting!

Continuing bird.   Discovered by Jane Azzaro.  I was hiking up the Panther Trail for a second sweep for the Trogon at about 5pm, when I paused to talk shop with Justin Bosler who was making his way downstream.  While we were standing there, I was facing west and saw a large grayish bird fly across the trail at about eye level, some 50yds upstream, and seemingly land near the south edge of the trail.  The added flash of pink-red seen in flight made me immediately think I was on the Trogon.  I quickly called out to Justin, and we made our way up the trail to close the gap, and found the Trogon on a low perch.  The bird then flew back to the creek area and began to flycatch.  Eventually, many birders converged on the site and had excellent extended views as the bird slowly made its way downstream.  Last seen flying to the north slope of the creek.  Classic large Trogon shaped bird, with an overall gray-greenish brown stocky/plump body, large round-blockish head, grayish face, dark lores, big striking dark eyes with pale/reddish eye ring, white wedge behind eye, bulky short yellow bill, long rich brown squared off tail with unique fine black and white barred edging.  Dingy pale below, grayish green breast, and distinct pink-red undertail coverts.   Fantastic looks with 8x42s and photographed.
Continuing bird.   Next to bridge eating berries from pyracantha Bush.   100 yards from parking area

Observation Details: What looks like the same individual immature male that overwintered in the Portal area—moving back and forth between downtown Portal and Cave Creek Ranch—spent at least 45 minutes foraging in our yard late this morning (11:15-noon). I watched it hover-glean insects in the elms and live oaks briefly and then spend 25 minutes foraging in the leafless mesquites. It would sit, looking around, studying the nearby bare branches, and then make a short flight, hovering to glean something small and dark (pink-purplish) from the branches, usually near the nodes. It even landed on a low rock wall just above ground level. Slowly, it then worked its way up the canyon—toward Cave Creek Ranch. I examined the branches and nodes of the mesquites closely but failed to find anything that seemed edible. In the past I’ve watched a N. Beardless-Tyrannulet forage in these same mesquites, successfully eating tiny purplish galls. Photos.

continuing bird since Jan 27. larger than scrub-jay, long tail with squared tip, pot-bellied no-necked appearance, unique stout bill shape somewhat tanager-like--bright cheddar cheese in color, dark olive-gray head and neck with white "ear spot" below eye, reddish orbital ring, olive-gray upper chest with white band above gray breast, then white and bright pinkish belly, distinctive pattern of fine black barring on white outer rectrices, upperparts darker and somewhat iridescent in deep olive-gray except for noticeable coppery cast to uppertail. photos to follow. another observer had the bird as we arrived at 14:45--usual location "midway" along Panther Canyon trail--we had the bird in view over the next 10 mins as it foraged and moved along the south slope and creekbed away from the Comal River. at that point the bird flew higher up on the south slope and we lost it, presumably as it continued moving along a well-defined side canyon coming in from the south. so far as I know the bird was not relocated over the next 2 hours despite efforts by multiple observers.

Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

Observation Details: Continuing female viewed from homeowner's kitchen window.  She said it had been coming for a month or two, and perching outside her window.  They had put out some blueberries for the bird which it had been eating. Homeowner invited a select group of about 10 people who had messaged her privately on Facebook, but does not want the location known generally.  Only three previous records of the species from Maricopa County (per the book), and only one previous record in eBird. The tail and rump color of this bird are consistent with the expected Coppery-tailed subspecies group and not elegans group.
heard calling fist, then great looks, photos coming

Continuing bird.   Discovered by Jane Azzaro.  I was hiking up the Panther Trail for a second sweep for the Trogon at about 5pm, when I paused to talk shop with Justin Bosler who was making his way downstream.  While we were standing there, I was facing west and saw a large grayish bird fly across the trail at about eye level, some 50yds upstream, and seemingly land near the south edge of the trail.  The added flash of pink-red seen in flight made me immediately think I was on the Trogon.  I quickly called out to Justin, and we made our way up the trail to close the gap, and found the Trogon on a low perch.  The bird then flew back to the creek area and began to flycatch.  Eventually, many birders converged on the site and had excellent extended views as the bird slowly made its way downstream.  Last seen flying to the north slope of the creek.  Classic large Trogon shaped bird, with an overall gray-greenish brown stocky/plump body, large round-blockish head, grayish face, dark lores, big striking dark eyes with pale/reddish eye ring, white wedge behind eye, bulky short yellow bill, long rich brown squared off tail with unique fine black and white barred edging.  Dingy pale below, grayish green breast, and distinct pink-red undertail coverts.   Fantastic looks with 8x42s and photographed.

Observation Details: Located the bird at 12:30 PM after hours of searching. These instructions are if you are coming up the trail from Landa Park. The bird was located near the bench that is off the trail about 20 yards on the west side (left side) of the trail about half way up the trail. There are a few benches that you will pass within 100 to 200 yards of the road that are right by the trail go past these. About 12:15 I was coming back down the trail headed to the park for a break, when I got near the bench I noticed a few birders coming up the trail, taking my eye off the trees briefly. The bird flushed over my head and landed about 10 yards from us. The bird was quite active and a number of us heard it vocalize a couple of times as it moved from one tree to the other. Great looks at the bird as it moved down the trail for at least 45 minutes. About 10 to 12 birders during this time.

Stunning looks at a male, heard first, than seen in a exposed branch of a tree directly above the pull out on the west side of the road.  Unmistakable, green back, gray wings, white faintly barred tail, red belly bordered by a white stripe above, yellow beak and surrounding the dark eyes.  When it called, its entire body rocked slightly.  First called a couple times, then flew and hover-plucked a fruit of some sort (I wish I knew what) and ate it, then flying to briefly hover closely outside a cavity in an Arizona sycamore just down towards the creek from the pull off and flew off.  Presumed nest site???

continuing bird since Jan 27. larger than scrub-jay, long tail with squared tip, pot-bellied no-necked appearance, unique stout bill shape somewhat tanager-like--bright cheddar cheese in color, dark olive-gray head and neck with white "ear spot" below eye, reddish orbital ring, olive-gray upper chest with white band above gray breast, then white and bright pinkish belly, distinctive pattern of fine black barring on white outer rectrices, upperparts darker and somewhat iridescent in deep olive-gray except for noticeable coppery cast to uppertail. photos to follow. another observer had the bird as we arrived at 14:45--usual location "midway" along Panther Canyon trail--we had the bird in view over the next 10 mins as it foraged and moved along the south slope and creekbed away from the Comal River. at that point the bird flew higher up on the south slope and we lost it, presumably as it continued moving along a well-defined side canyon coming in from the south. so far as I know the bird was not relocated over the next 2 hours despite efforts by multiple observers.

Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

An Elegant Trogon continued in the trees adjacent to the Panther Canyon Trail in Landa Park in New Braunfels . I observed and photographed the Elegant Trogon from about 12:38 pm until 1:38 pm. The trogon flew short distances from branch to branch and primarily perched on the lower and mid-level branches of the trees of the slopes of the canyon adjacent to the trail. Although the trogon was primarily silent, it once vocalized for a few seconds with a "clucking" call.  During the period that I observed and photographed the Elegant Trogon, it was also observed and photographed by numerous other individuals.

The bird was located near the bench that is off the trail about 20 yards on the west side (left side) of the trail about half way up the trail. There are a few benches that you will pass within 100 to 200 yards of the road that are right by the trail go past these. About 12:15 I was coming back down the trail headed to the park for a break, when I got near the bench I noticed a few birders coming up the trail, taking my eye off the trees briefly. The bird flushed over my head and landed about 10 yards from us. The bird was quite active and a number of us heard it vocalize a couple of times as it moved from one tree to the other. Great looks at the bird as it moved down the trail for at least 45 minutes. About 10 to 12 birders during this time.

Continuing female. Seen just before 3 pm. Red under tail, whiter belly, square tail, short yellow bill and white by eye. Moving along dry creek bed. Seen by a large dedicated group of birders. Seen again at 5:10 pm; great show catching bugs and vocalizing. Photos are from evening sighting.

Locality: Panther Canyon Nature Trail - Landa Park, New Braunfels
Observation Details: Found the previous weekend (1/27/18) but reported on Saturday night (2/3) after being properly identified; Hadn't seen a positive report all morning but decided to head down and search. Upon arriving, Eric Carpenter gave me the heads up that the bird had been refound and was being observed midway along the Panther Canyon Trail. Several folks helped us get on the bird, which was actively moving from tree to tree and primarily along the main creek wash.   The bird appeared to be a female with prominent white mark behind the eye, red orbital ring, and yellow bill. Grayish head and chest, which terminated abruptly, forming a white collar. Rosy belly and vent, grayish/green back, coppery central tail feathers, and unique barred undertail pattern.   It made its way up a steep wash on the side of the hill and wasn't seen again for over an hour, appearing around 5:23pm near the exact spot it was reported on Sunday evening. We observed the bird much longer and at a closer distance than earlier, but in much poorer lighting.

Adult male seen feeding on Pyrocantha several times. Dark emerald upperparts with blackish on the head with sharply contrasting yellow bill. Silvery upperwkng converts. Coppery sheen to uppersurface of tail. Thin vermiculated hashwork on the undertail surface with some thicker dark bands. White outer retrices. Heard giving cooing warbled (aggitated?) call. Irregular winter visitor, especially at higher elevations, though seem to be becoming more regular in the colder months.

Male at stream crossing up trail from the “bathtub”. Feeding high in the outer branches of tall Douglas-firs and Az. Cypress. He seems to have a buildup of pitch on his lower mandible that’s bothering him as he’s trying aggressively to remove it by rubbing his beak on branches, though not having much success. I’m guessing he’s eating budworms in the new growth of the Doug-firs as he’ll fly to the new needles, hover, pick at the needles, and return to previous branch. Occasionally came down to creek to bath.

Observation Details: male

male and female, not together. Male was down on ground where it picked up a tail full of burrs from a bamboo/grass-like understory plant that is very a very common component of forest here. He managed to clean his tail off but still had a few burrs stuck to his face when I last saw him

Photo’s. Using the area between the picnic area parking lot and the stream. This bird was hunting constantly, despite multiple people watching it. In one instance it flew approx. 20 yards straight toward me and pounced on a lizard about 10’ from my feet, then hopped up to a low branch so close that I had to back up to get a photo! Very exciting. This was one of my most memorable birds in my young birding days, and now 35 years later, it is still just as exciting!

Worked Pima County portion from Whitehorse Picnic Area down to almost Proctor Rd & up to Madera Picnic Area (twice) in search of trogon. Finall at 11:15 it flew into a tree right next to us at Madera Picnic Area. It eventually flew to the “famous” pyracantha bush & ate several berries before moving down canyon a short distance. Eventually m.obs. were present too. Photos tba.
Continuing. Found early in the morning by the two wooden bridges, just downstream of the Madera PA. Perched and vocalizing. Photos.

Photos. Just east of sunny flat. Spotted first by my non-birding partner who thought “this is either really common or really rare.”  Ha! It hopped around us for a while and even as we were walking away kept flying near. Super cool! Probably the same individual that was spotted at Cave Creek resort on the 19th

Calling in the woods along the creek in the canyon. I spotted it low in the understory, looking around and giving its odd bark-like call every 20-30 second. It had an odd habit of turning its head very slowly, like someone checking over his shoulder to see if anyone else is in on the joke. I followed it as it moved through the trees, never getting more than three or four feet off the ground.

Locality: Madera Canyon--Mt. Wrightson Picnic Area & Upper Canyon Trails

Observation Details: At 3:12 pm I heard the Trogon for the first time. I realized we needed to go higher after getting in a good spot to listen to the calls. Once I reached the location where it sounded the closest I then realized there were 2 Trogons. At 3:42 we got our first eyes on 1 Trogon pretty close. Then the second Trogon appeared as well.  2 male Trogons we observed until we left the location at 4:50pm. We just sat down and watched them calling back and forth, going from tree to tree. Was able to record several videos. At 450 one had moved higher up the mountain out of sight and the other lower. They were still calling. 31.700239,-110.877164 Good Luck! My best birding experience... just us and the Trogons for an hour

Media notes: With its mouth still full, it was looking around for additional food items.
Observation Details: What looks like the same individual immature male that overwintered in the Portal area—moving back and forth between downtown Portal and Cave Creek Ranch—spent at least 45 minutes foraging in our yard late this morning (11:15-noon). I watched it hover-glean insects in the elms and live oaks briefly and then spend 25 minutes foraging in the leafless mesquites. It would sit, looking around, studying the nearby bare branches, and then make a short flight, hovering to glean something small and dark (pink-purplish) from the branches, usually near the nodes. It even landed on a low rock wall just above ground level. Slowly, it then worked its way up the canyon—toward Cave Creek Ranch. I examined the branches and nodes of the mesquites closely but failed to find anything that seemed edible. In the past I’ve watched a N. Beardless-Tyrannulet forage in these same mesquites, successfully eating tiny purplish galls. Photos.

Media notes: Ca. 5' above ground in a leafless mesquite

Absolutely stunning views of a male in exquisite morning light just down stream from the picnic area and also across the road towards Bog Springs entry rd. Classic trogon shape; long narrow wings, chunky body, large rounded head, long thick tail expanding near tip, and dump-truck rump. Bluish-green iridescence to head and upper breast, thin white collar, scarlet belly and vent. Waxy yellow bill. Salt and peppered wing coverts. Thin pinkish orbital ring around eye. Photos.

Media notes: Male Elegant Trogon perched next to nest cavity.
Observation Details: One called at 05:57. Female hunting along the creek, in the center of our territory at 06:15, silent. Male flew in at 06:53. Immediately female displaced male on branch. Both silent.  At 07:47 one flew over headed upstream.  At 08:21 a male was heard upstream of the center of our territory but close. We located him....still calling at 08:27. He stayed at his perch till 08:38 then moved downstream, but not far. He stayed at the second perch till 08:50. At third perch till 09:14 then dropped about 10 feet lower. At 09:17 the male chased an Apache Fox Squirrel out of a nearby Douglas-fir. At 09:22 he dropped out of sight behind a screen of small trees, but not far away.  We crossed the creek to check the sycamores for cavities. At 09:38 the male perched a few feet over our heads, then flew to the apparent nest cavity in a sycamore, and put his head inside. We left him in peace, perched immediately in front of the cavity.

Locality: Garden Canyon Rd--BETWEEN Upper Picnic Area and Sawmill Canyon
Observation Details: This individual was sighted first, both on the uphill and then returning downhill about an hour later. Elevation was 5708 feet, along the creek, where the road has square concrete pavers (31.46469, -110.36146). The location was much higher elevation than the other two. I was able to get someone in a car on it also to enjoy great looks. The first sighting, on our ascent, it was silent, by the water, and came down to the creek. The second sighting, on our descent, it was feeding, sallying out and returning to either the same branch or slightly different position. It also called softly a few times. This individual was a male, with extensive red on the breast and belly and a white band. This was the first time I saw the "copper" tail: the sun hit the tail at a certain angle and it actually looked like metallic copper.

Locality: Panther Canyon Nature Trail, New Braunfels
Observation Details: Located the bird at 12:30 PM after hours of searching. These instructions are if you are coming up the trail from Landa Park. The bird was located near the bench that is off the trail about 20 yards on the west side (left side) of the trail about half way up the trail. There are a few benches that you will pass within 100 to 200 yards of the road that are right by the trail go past these. About 12:15 I was coming back down the trail headed to the park for a break, when I got near the bench I noticed a few birders coming up the trail, taking my eye off the trees briefly. The bird flushed over my head and landed about 10 yards from us. The bird was quite active and a number of us heard it vocalize a couple of times as it moved from one tree to the other. Great looks at the bird as it moved down the trail for at least 45 minutes. About 10 to 12 birders during this time.

Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

Male at stream crossing up trail from the “bathtub”. Feeding high in the outer branches of tall Douglas-firs and Az. Cypress. He seems to have a buildup of pitch on his lower mandible that’s bothering him as he’s trying aggressively to remove it by rubbing his beak on branches, though not having much success. I’m guessing he’s eating budworms in the new growth of the Doug-firs as he’ll fly to the new needles, hover, pick at the needles, and return to previous branch. Occasionally came down to creek to bath.

Continuing. Thanks to Vincent and Justin for locating this bird on the trail. Green head and back, long green tail with black tips, with outer tail feathers with black stripes on white. Yellow bill with orangish eye ring with white “teardrop” stripe falling down from behind the eye. Darker gray cheeks. White breast band above a light grayish green breast  and bright red lower belly and UTC. Pics. Viewed with 15-20 other birders for several minutes from 15-20 feet.

Continuing bird.   Discovered by Jane Azzaro.  I was hiking up the Panther Trail for a second sweep for the Trogon at about 5pm, when I paused to talk shop with Justin Bosler who was making his way downstream.  While we were standing there, I was facing west and saw a large grayish bird fly across the trail at about eye level, some 50yds upstream, and seemingly land near the south edge of the trail.  The added flash of pink-red seen in flight made me immediately think I was on the Trogon.  I quickly called out to Justin, and we made our way up the trail to close the gap, and found the Trogon on a low perch.  The bird then flew back to the creek area and began to flycatch.  Eventually, many birders converged on the site and had excellent extended views as the bird slowly made its way downstream.  Last seen flying to the north slope of the creek.  Classic large Trogon shaped bird, with an overall gray-greenish brown stocky/plump body, large round-blockish head, grayish face, dark lores, big striking dark eyes with pale/reddish eye ring, white wedge behind eye, bulky short yellow bill, long rich brown squared off tail with unique fine black and white barred edging.  Dingy pale below, grayish green breast, and distinct pink-red undertail coverts.   Fantastic looks with 8x42s and photographed.

Locality: Panther Canyon Nature Trail - Landa Park, New Braunfels
Observation Details: Found the previous weekend (1/27/18) but reported on Saturday night (2/3) after being properly identified; Hadn't seen a positive report all morning but decided to head down and search. Upon arriving, Eric Carpenter gave me the heads up that the bird had been refound and was being observed midway along the Panther Canyon Trail. Several folks helped us get on the bird, which was actively moving from tree to tree and primarily along the main creek wash.   The bird appeared to be a female with prominent white mark behind the eye, red orbital ring, and yellow bill. Grayish head and chest, which terminated abruptly, forming a white collar. Rosy belly and vent, grayish/green back, coppery central tail feathers, and unique barred undertail pattern.   It made its way up a steep wash on the side of the hill and wasn't seen again for over an hour, appearing around 5:23pm near the exact spot it was reported on Sunday evening. We observed the bird much longer and at a closer distance than earlier, but in much poorer lighting.

Media notes: Elegant Trogon, immature male, Cave Creek Ranch, Portal, Cochise County, AZ, November 30, 2021, Carol R.  Comeau
Observation Details: Continuing immature male. This is the same bird we saw on our hillside on November 24th. It came in twice during the observation period. The first sighting was at 10:20 AM. From the office porch we observed the bird come into the right side of the large pyracantha bush next to the water feature. It plucked and ate a few berries- perching in the pyracantha bush, a bare branched tree to the right, and  on the agave stalk with a hanging feeder.

Immature female with white margins on tail and white vertical teardrop marks behind eyes, red eye rings; bill short, stout, and golden yellow.  Rose-red lower belly and paler undertail coverts, chest light grey, narrow collar off-white, throat and cowl darker grey-brown but lighter than head. Head, back, and wings gray-brown. Center tail feathers coppery brown on dorsal, white with distinct black barring on ventral. Seen on Panther Canyon trail which follows a rocky, dry streambed above Comal Springs. Trogon was on various perches and flying - noted large, nearly rectangular wings. Seen eating berries.

Continuing bird. Photos. ‘Canescens’ or ‘ambiguus’?Observed approximately 0.6 km up the canyon trail.  Actively foraging on what appeared to be green fruits--couldn't get confirmation of food items.  Classic trogon profile with long square-tipped tail.  Upperside of tail reddish brown; underside finely marked with dark gray wavy lines on white background.  White post-ocular stripe diagnostic--bordered with blackish edges.  Pinkish-red belly and undertail coverts.  Bold yellow bill.  Beady black eye with reddish orbital ring.

Media notes: On rock wall 1.5' above ground level, after having hover-gleaned in background mesquite
Observation Details: What looks like the same individual immature male that overwintered in the Portal area—moving back and forth between downtown Portal and Cave Creek Ranch—spent at least 45 minutes foraging in our yard late this morning (11:15-noon). I watched it hover-glean insects in the elms and live oaks briefly and then spend 25 minutes foraging in the leafless mesquites. It would sit, looking around, studying the nearby bare branches, and then make a short flight, hovering to glean something small and dark (pink-purplish) from the branches, usually near the nodes. It even landed on a low rock wall just above ground level. Slowly, it then worked its way up the canyon—toward Cave Creek Ranch. I examined the branches and nodes of the mesquites closely but failed to find anything that seemed edible. In the past I’ve watched a N. Beardless-Tyrannulet forage in these same mesquites, successfully eating tiny purplish galls. Photos.

Two birds heard at 6:49, still calling at 7:17; approx. location 31.51184, -110.39021, up slope E of road. Presumed pair: one giving slow, higher pitched “koink koink”; the other giving fast, lower pitched “kow kow kow”. At 8:00, farther up canyon, possibly the same pair seen investigating cavity in dead oak W of road in main drainage. Female gave “kow kow kow” call and ate caterpillar while male was in cavity. Then the male emerged and perched while the female entered and stayed in cavity at least 7 minutes (we moved up canyon). At 10:00 on our return, the male was giving “kow kow kow” calls near the first cavity, then he entered another cavity in a different dead tree and continued calling (from inside the cavity, unseen) for 6-8 more minutes. Female not seen or heard. Down canyon about 0.25 mile a different male was seen and photographed and recorded at 10:30. Same male photographed again 0.4 mile downstream at 11:15.

Media notes: Perched after hover-plucking grapes
Observation Details: A continuing juvenile that was here at sunset yesterday and undetected this morning until it called and flew into the mustang grapevine where it had fed last evening. This morning it flutter-plucked grapes at least three times and then caught several insects from nearby junipers and Rocky Mountain Locusts, then sat quietly for 40+ minutes on a juniper branch directly above the creek a bit downstream. It sat there, preening, even as a Cooper’s Hawk flew right under it on a hunting trip down the creek. Eventually it returned to the original grapevine area, grabbing something from the juniper, and then flew upcreek, giving its call. [When I checked again at 3:45PM, the photographed juvenile was once again grabbing grapes on the wing.]
Adult males; one feeding in Juniperus deppeana (alligator juniper), the other plucking fruits from Vitis arizonica (canyon grape) and perching low in the drainage.

Immature male (originally thought to be a female, but has green on back) and then a male farther up with another trogon not as well seen. Feeding on grape. And then two juveniles. One was fed by the adult male. Obvious family group. The first bird I saw much lower down may not be associated with the family, which would make five. Mostly silent, but heard a chatter call a few times. Accipiter in the area. On the way down, confirmed two males (on brighter), so five birds at the very least. Photos of each. Will upload.

Locality: stakeout Elegant Trogon, N Pier Mountain Rd (2025)
Observation Details: ***rare. Found by MW on Friday and CM on Saturday in their back yards, today it was perched in the front yards along the street. Seen by several of the residents of the west side of the street in their back yards overlooking the wash. Visitors welcome to park along N Pier Mountain Rd. and walk, checking the larger trees, but the bird evidently moves around a lot and spends most of the days in parts unknown; evening seems to be when most sightings occur. At least three lowland sightings from the Tucson area: Sweetwater (Jun 2008), west Tucson (July 2021), central Tucson (Dec 2023) plus a few others.

Observation Details: Photo’s. Using the area between the picnic area parking lot and the stream. This bird was hunting constantly, despite multiple people watching it. In one instance it flew approx. 20 yards straight toward me and pounced on a lizard about 10’ from my feet, then hopped up to a low branch so close that I had to back up to get a photo! Very exciting. This was one of my most memorable birds in my young birding days, and now 35 years later, it is still just as exciting!

Worked Pima County portion from Whitehorse Picnic Area down to almost Proctor Rd & up to Madera Picnic Area (twice) in search of trogon. Finall at 11:15 it flew into a tree right next to us at Madera Picnic Area. It eventually flew to the “famous” pyracantha bush & ate several berries before moving down canyon a short distance. Eventually m.obs. were present too. Photos tba.

Observation Details: Calling in the woods along the creek in the canyon. I spotted it low in the understory, looking around and giving its odd bark-like call every 20-30 second. It had an odd habit of turning its head very slowly, like someone checking over his shoulder to see if anyone else is in on the joke. I followed it as it moved through the trees, never getting more than three or four feet off the ground.

Locality: 128 Ivy Hill Ct, Santa Teresa US-NM 31.84935, -106.63924
Observation Details: Absolutely amazing! After seeing a good photo of this bird taken at 7:30 last evening, I contacted Sarah about coming over this morning. Soon after I arrived I heard the rolling chatter call coming from uphill approximately 7:11 a.m. Somewhat later I heard the croak call from same direction/area. Later, at about 8:45 PHOTOS! This bird in NOT chaseable. It is within a gated community with very strictly controlled access.

Heard calling first, then located a male about 30 feet up in a Douglas Fir. Watched the bird for about half an hour as it moved from perch to perch, slowly foraging. Heard it call four times. Perches ranged from about 20-35 feet high. Large sycamores and some oaks in the area, though most of the perches we saw the bird use were conifers. Bird was seen about a mile and a quarter up the trail, after a stream crossing with a fairly sizable pool of water in it.

Locality: Reserva Ecológica Sierra de San Juan--La Noria

Observation Details: Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

Observation Details: Continuing immature male. Seen feeding in hackberry trees (large trees on the right side of road as you get towards the office) at 1:15 PM. I also watched the pyracantha berries by the water feature but did not see it come in to feed during my observation period. Photos.

Coming back down the Carrie Nation Trail, just below the lowest creek crossing, I stopped to look for a bird making a towhee-like mew (which I never found); while searching for it, an adult male trogon flew in silently and perched overhead. My husband was up-trail from the bird and got clear photos of its back, it was directly over my head, and I got partially blocked shots of its belly. It never vocalized. We watched it for a couple of minutes until it flew across the creek and out of sight. Note that the timestamp on the second photo (of bird's belly) is accurate; the first photo's timestamp is off by more than an hour: both photos were taken at the same time, right around 11 am 12 Sept 2021

Observation Details: Three nestlings visible in nest hole.  Nestlings making constant pip sounds- which increased during  feedings. Both adults coming in consistently during the observation period. Prey items included katydids, praying mantids, walking sticks, and larva.

Adult male seen feeding on Pyrocantha several times. Dark emerald upperparts with blackish on the head with sharply contrasting yellow bill. Silvery upperwkng converts. Coppery sheen to uppersurface of tail. Thin vermiculated hashwork on the undertail surface with some thicker dark bands. White outer retrices. Heard giving cooing warbled (aggitated?) call. Irregular winter visitor, especially at higher elevations, though seem to be becoming more regular in the colder months.

I was coming down the trail towards Proctor and was about .4 miles from Madera Picnic Area when I saw group of 6 or 8 persons crouched down on the trail looking at a mature male  Elegant Trogon on a branch only three feet above the trail and only about ten feet from them!   How lucky I thought and as I was about to take a photo, one of their kids let out a blood-curdling scream and the Trogon flew to a tree close to myself and another woman...we followed it around to about five different trees where it would perch and wait for an insect,  I presume.    Eventually it flew down canyon.  Amazing how tolerant of people these birds are!

Locality: Estero Llano Grande SP--Tropical Zone only
Observation Details: Adult female continuing here since November 23, 2020. Found hiding in the shade, low in dense brush in the center of the Tropical Zone. Sitting more or less motionless, other than slowly tilting its head around and panting (very hot today). It did move between 3 perches in a small area. Initially spotted behind large mailbox #123 at (26.1247855, -97.9577671); straight back Lakeview Drive from entrance gate. Replacing tail feathers. Reddish undertail coverts. Berry residue on bill. Only the 3rd eBird record for the LRGV and 4th for Texas. Photos.

Media notes: Seen & heard at this location by many. Seen defending a cavity nest hole high up on a dead Sycamore snag adjacent to where ELTR was calling out. Defending the cavity from 3 NOFL flying to the cavity hole.
Observation Details: 1st sighting & call about 150 yds. up from S Fork Cave Creek Trailhead @ 06:00. Male was detected high in pine tree, calling several times. Poor photograph, but photo file shows GPS location GPS: 31.870,-109.187.  2nd ELTR opportunity was heard only at GPS: 31.863,-109.190 at the center spot of my assigned territory (above second crossing) across the creek on the south side. The call was that of a solitary male.  3rd ELTR was sighted & heard en route back to the S Fork Cave Creek trailhead about 11:30 am. Was seen defending a cavity nest on an adjacent dead Sycamore snag adjacent from where the male was calling. The ELTR was observed chasing off three different NOFL from the cavity hole when they approached it. Many obs. were taking photos. It was not determined if this individual was the same one reported several hours earlier at 06:00 closer to the trailhead. The third individual seen and photographed well (2) was seen at GPS: 31.869,-109.188. Phone photo, included, also showed same GPS location.

I was bringing my feeders back out after a rain storm when I saw a bird fly up to one of my feeders. It perched on the top of one of my woodpecker feeders. I noticed the white flared tail when it perched and thought it was a dove. As I got closer I noticed that it was squatter then a dove and had a thick yellow bill. I also noticed the white teardrop coming down from its eye. It had a darker, gray-green hood and lighter breast. It sat on the feeder pole for a minute or two while I took pictures. When I started to back away it flew across the street into the neighbors olive tree. I was able to see some red feathering in the center of the tail as it flew away. I think it was female due to the white teardrop and the relatively uniform back color. I'm not sure if it was a coppery-tailed or elegant.

I observed an adult male trogon for several minutes from about 15m while it perched in Netleaf hackberry and Fremont cottonwood along the west end of the Creek Trail. It was also repeatedly making a clucking call of several low notes.  The trogon had a green head and back, a coppery colored tail top, and a bright red belly separated from the green chest by a white band. An apparent casual visitor at this location. This male is notably different from the female/immature that I observed on 17 December at the Preserve.

Se adjuntan fotos

Observation Details: Male at stream crossing up trail from the “bathtub”. Feeding high in the outer branches of tall Douglas-firs and Az. Cypress. He seems to have a buildup of pitch on his lower mandible that’s bothering him as he’s trying aggressively to remove it by rubbing his beak on branches, though not having much success. I’m guessing he’s eating budworms in the new growth of the Doug-firs as he’ll fly to the new needles, hover, pick at the needles, and return to previous branch. Occasionally came down to creek to bath.

Locality: Estero Llano Grande SP--Tropical Zone only
Observation Details: Continuing immature, photographed at 26.1247939, -97.9586727. Initially heard giving loud distinctive cackles about halfway down Tyrannulet Rd of Tropical Area. Eventually found sitting in tangle, occasionally sallying out and generally moving northward (towards Green Jay Trl). Largish bird with coppery coloration on upper tail surface, slightly duller warm brown upperparts. Rose-colored undertail coverts. Brownish head with distinctive vertical white mark on either side of the face. Short bright yellow bill. Red colored orbital ring. Undertail mostly white with dark vermiculation, white outer retrices splayed in flight.

Male trogon seen at 4:45 PM approximately one mile up the trail. The bird flew across the trail from the west to east about 100 feet past the entering national forest sign right where the trail makes the first switchback across the creek. He sat on a lower branch of a sycamore tree and then dropped down onto a three foot tree stump on the ground. He then briefly flew up and caught a large insect and went back into the lower part of the sycamore tree and ate it. I spent about five minutes with the bird before he flew north up the creek. I will attach photos of the trogon eating the insect and perched on the short tree stump.

Stunning looks at a male, heard first, than seen in a exposed branch of a tree directly above the pull out on the west side of the road.  Unmistakable, green back, gray wings, white faintly barred tail, red belly bordered by a white stripe above, yellow beak and surrounding the dark eyes.  When it called, its entire body rocked slightly.  First called a couple times, then flew and hover-plucked a fruit of some sort (I wish I knew what) and ate it, then flying to briefly hover closely outside a cavity in an Arizona sycamore just down towards the creek from the pull off and flew off.  Presumed nest site???

Media notes: Elegant Trogon
Observation Details: Barb M. told us to take the trail 0.1mi up canyon from the amphitheater bridge.  Sure enough, I soon heard a distinctive 'bark'.  My ears are a bit wonky, but these birds always sound like they use a mechanical arf to communicate.  The two birds were in a tree just upslope from a rock fall.  I checked my Garmin.  It read 0.1mi.  Barb is good!  Thanks Barb.  Keith walked a short distance further to see if he could get a better picture.  About then, one Trogon flew off and the other came closer to us.  Gradually, it circled around us, stopping several times for photo ops.  By the time we returned to the car, it was waiting for us in the tree at the parking lot end of the bridge.

continuing bird since Jan 27. larger than scrub-jay, long tail with squared tip, pot-bellied no-necked appearance, unique stout bill shape somewhat tanager-like--bright cheddar cheese in color, dark olive-gray head and neck with white "ear spot" below eye, reddish orbital ring, olive-gray upper chest with white band above gray breast, then white and bright pinkish belly, distinctive pattern of fine black barring on white outer rectrices, upperparts darker and somewhat iridescent in deep olive-gray except for noticeable coppery cast to uppertail. photos to follow. another observer had the bird as we arrived at 14:45--usual location "midway" along Panther Canyon trail--we had the bird in view over the next 10 mins as it foraged and moved along the south slope and creekbed away from the Comal River. at that point the bird flew higher up on the south slope and we lost it, presumably as it continued moving along a well-defined side canyon coming in from the south. so far as I know the bird was not relocated over the next 2 hours despite efforts by multiple observers.

Immature female with white margins on tail and white vertical teardrop marks behind eyes, red eye rings; bill short, stout, and golden yellow.  Rose-red lower belly and paler undertail coverts, chest light grey, narrow collar off-white, throat and cowl darker grey-brown but lighter than head. Head, back, and wings gray-brown. Center tail feathers coppery brown on dorsal, white with distinct black barring on ventral. Seen on Panther Canyon trail which follows a rocky, dry streambed above Comal Springs. Trogon was on various perches and flying - noted large, nearly rectangular wings. Seen eating berries.
Continuing. Photos

Observation Details: Please see attached photos.  Blue Jay sized, grayish bird with long, flat tail.  Stout, yellow bill.  Yellow eye ring.  White, horizontal line behind eye.  Pinkish-red under tail.  Black and white pattern on outer tail feathers.  About twenty five birders were present.  We saw the bird around 1:30 p.m., and watched it for at least 10 minutes.  Probably same bird present at this location for at least a week.  Thanks, Dennis Shepler, for posting today's sighting on Texbirds Facebook.

Seen and photographed by this observer at 2:51 PM about halfway up Panther Canyon, Landa Park.  Clearly, an Elegant Trogon, the dorsal region of the bird was a brownish gray with a long copper colored tail.  The throat was a dark gray and the chest and belly were a lighter gray with a white streak across the breast just below the throat.  The under-tail coverts were a rosy reddish color. The bill was a pale yellowish and the bird had a white streak behind the eye that was bordered on the rear with black.  The outer three graduated rectrices were black and white striped.  Observed in subdued afternoon sunlight to the rear of the observer shining on the bird.  Seen with 10X42 Swarovski binoculars.  I am familiar with this species having seen it many times while living in Costa Rica and on visits to SE AZ.

Continuing female. Seen just before 3 pm. Red under tail, whiter belly, square tail, short yellow bill and white by eye. Moving along dry creek bed. Seen by a large dedicated group of birders. Seen again at 5:10 pm; great show catching bugs and vocalizing. Photos are from evening sighting.

Locality: Panther Canyon Nature Trail - Landa Park, New Braunfels
Observation Details: Found the previous weekend (1/27/18) but reported on Saturday night (2/3) after being properly identified; Hadn't seen a positive report all morning but decided to head down and search. Upon arriving, Eric Carpenter gave me the heads up that the bird had been refound and was being observed midway along the Panther Canyon Trail. Several folks helped us get on the bird, which was actively moving from tree to tree and primarily along the main creek wash.   The bird appeared to be a female with prominent white mark behind the eye, red orbital ring, and yellow bill. Grayish head and chest, which terminated abruptly, forming a white collar. Rosy belly and vent, grayish/green back, coppery central tail feathers, and unique barred undertail pattern.   It made its way up a steep wash on the side of the hill and wasn't seen again for over an hour, appearing around 5:23pm near the exact spot it was reported on Sunday evening. We observed the bird much longer and at a closer distance than earlier, but in much poorer lighting.

Observation Details: 3 males appeared to be having a vocal territory battle. Could hear the barking from 3 locations and occasionally 2 or 3 were barking at the same time. Good look at one of the 3. These were closer to Maple camp end of trail than to picnic area and it was 1:30 pm.  4th bird, also male, was in a Sycamore cavity closer to picnic area. It was half out of the hole barking without pause for at least 20 minutes. Then it came out and perched on a limb about 6 ft from hole and continued barking. No sign of any females. This was around 2:30 PM.

Locality: S Fork Rd (from pin to bridge)
Observation Details: WOW LIFER! I was driving to the south fork hotspot when I glanced over and saw a trogon perched 10 feet away from me. Followed him into the woods along the dried up stream bed. Got good looks at two adult males. They would sit completely still then occasionally burst into flight to catch bugs. There might of been a female nearby but I didn’t get good looks. Last place I saw them was from the creek bed here: (31.87421° N, 109.18137° W), they were moving upslope and probably to the right (so southwest from the coordinates). Then spotted a female 5 minutes later up the road a bit here: (31.87421° N, 109.18137° W). She stayed along the creek (with water) catching bugs.

Male at nest. Lifer! Very suspenseful chase. Heard singing from quite a distance, then we slowly crept closer until it sounded like it was right above us. It continued to elude while we walked around the tree in silent confusion trying to see it. Finally michael spotted it in the nest, and I saw it briefly before it flew out and perched in the open in a conifer. It continued to sing as we watched it for several minutes, before finally flushing upstream. We waited at least half an hour for its return but it never did. Fantastic looks at a fantastic bird

Locality: Ramsey Canyon Preserve (formerly Mile Hi Ranch)

Observation Details: Encountered three individuals approximately 100 meters south of the junction of the old trailhead and new trail.  Initially we did not notice the hatch year bird until reviewing the photographs.  In the photograph you can see the female on the left showing red on the belly and the hatch year on the right with a white belly.  The male was approximately 10 meters above the pair.  On the return hike, we encountered the male and female again but did not see the hatch year. The female flew over the trail and our heads and landed in a tree. We studied her for a bit then heard the male calling about 10 meters down the trail and were able to locate him very low to the ground.

Media notes: Gleaning small, purplish, rounded food from the branches of the mesquite
Observation Details: What looks like the same individual immature male that overwintered in the Portal area—moving back and forth between downtown Portal and Cave Creek Ranch—spent at least 45 minutes foraging in our yard late this morning (11:15-noon). I watched it hover-glean insects in the elms and live oaks briefly and then spend 25 minutes foraging in the leafless mesquites. It would sit, looking around, studying the nearby bare branches, and then make a short flight, hovering to glean something small and dark (pink-purplish) from the branches, usually near the nodes. It even landed on a low rock wall just above ground level. Slowly, it then worked its way up the canyon—toward Cave Creek Ranch. I examined the branches and nodes of the mesquites closely but failed to find anything that seemed edible. In the past I’ve watched a N. Beardless-Tyrannulet forage in these same mesquites, successfully eating tiny purplish galls. Photos.

Observation Details: Two birds heard at 6:49, still calling at 7:17; approx. location 31.51184, -110.39021, up slope E of road. Presumed pair: one giving slow, higher pitched “koink koink”; the other giving fast, lower pitched “kow kow kow”. At 8:00, farther up canyon, possibly the same pair seen investigating cavity in dead oak W of road in main drainage. Female gave “kow kow kow” call and ate caterpillar while male was in cavity. Then the male emerged and perched while the female entered and stayed in cavity at least 7 minutes (we moved up canyon). At 10:00 on our return, the male was giving “kow kow kow” calls near the first cavity, then he entered another cavity in a different dead tree and continued calling (from inside the cavity, unseen) for 6-8 more minutes. Female not seen or heard. Down canyon about 0.25 mile a different male was seen and photographed and recorded at 10:30. Same male photographed again 0.4 mile downstream at 11:15.

Observation Details: A continuing juvenile (see photo). Calling intermittently from upstream, it came close only once while I was there.

Media notes: Panting in the heat
Observation Details: A continuing juvenile that was here at sunset yesterday and undetected this morning until it called and flew into the mustang grapevine where it had fed last evening. This morning it flutter-plucked grapes at least three times and then caught several insects from nearby junipers and Rocky Mountain Locusts, then sat quietly for 40+ minutes on a juniper branch directly above the creek a bit downstream. It sat there, preening, even as a Cooper’s Hawk flew right under it on a hunting trip down the creek. Eventually it returned to the original grapevine area, grabbing something from the juniper, and then flew upcreek, giving its call. [When I checked again at 3:45PM, the photographed juvenile was once again grabbing grapes on the wing.]

Continuing bird.   Discovered by Jane Azzaro.  I was hiking up the Panther Trail for a second sweep for the Trogon at about 5pm, when I paused to talk shop with Justin Bosler who was making his way downstream.  While we were standing there, I was facing west and saw a large grayish bird fly across the trail at about eye level, some 50yds upstream, and seemingly land near the south edge of the trail.  The added flash of pink-red seen in flight made me immediately think I was on the Trogon.  I quickly called out to Justin, and we made our way up the trail to close the gap, and found the Trogon on a low perch.  The bird then flew back to the creek area and began to flycatch.  Eventually, many birders converged on the site and had excellent extended views as the bird slowly made its way downstream.  Last seen flying to the north slope of the creek.  Classic large Trogon shaped bird, with an overall gray-greenish brown stocky/plump body, large round-blockish head, grayish face, dark lores, big striking dark eyes with pale/reddish eye ring, white wedge behind eye, bulky short yellow bill, long rich brown squared off tail with unique fine black and white barred edging.  Dingy pale below, grayish green breast, and distinct pink-red undertail coverts.   Fantastic looks with 8x42s and photographed.

Locality: Paco's Reserva de Flora y Fauna

Observation Details: After glimpsing a bird flying past the window and thinking "trogon?", went outside with binoculars and found a female ELTR perching about eye-level in an Alligator Juniper growing beneath a large Arizona Sycamore. Watched it flutter to a juniper branch and snatch something 2-3" long (and grayish) from the foliage and return to a perch to eat it. Went back for camera and obtained photos and video for the next several minutes as the bird continued to forage its way through the yard, during which time it found and ate another of what I presume was some kind of caterpillar. Wondering if this is the same bird I saw here on 10-03-2019 ...

Locality: Estero Llano Grande SP--Tropical Zone only
Observation Details: Saw at 9:40-9:45. Calm bird. Female, slate gray head, back and wings, vertical white mark behind eye, dark throat and bib, tawny chest, red belly and under-tail coverts, long tail with white underside and fine black barring. Perched on shaded branch about 5 ft above ground, in grassy area. Didn’t notice it until I was ~15 ft away, then I backed up. It allowed me to admire it for a few minutes, then flew to another snag, about 2 ft off the ground (!), another 20 ft away. Made a few low, chattering calls and settled right in. A few great photos! New county bird for me.

Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

Observation Details: Dodie Logue reported hearing and seeing an immature male trogon at 9:15 AM in the creek bed across from the Portal library annex. At 12:10 PM the bird was heard and seen calling on the hill above my house. The bird flew downhill back towards "downtown" Portal. There are many ripe pyracanthas around downtown Portal. Seen and photographed by this observer at 2:51 PM about halfway up Panther Canyon, Landa Park.  Clearly, an Elegant Trogon, the dorsal region of the bird was a brownish gray with a long copper colored tail.  The throat was a dark gray and the chest and belly were a lighter gray with a white streak across the breast just below the throat.  The under-tail coverts were a rosy reddish color. The bill was a pale yellowish and the bird had a white streak behind the eye that was bordered on the rear with black.  The outer three graduated rectrices were black and white striped.  Observed in subdued afternoon sunlight to the rear of the observer shining on the bird.  Seen with 10X42 Swarovski binoculars.  I am familiar with this species having seen it many times while living in Costa Rica and on visits to SE AZ.

Sitting more or less motionless, other than slowly tilting its head around and panting (very hot today). It did move between 3 perches in a small area. Initially spotted behind large mailbox #123 at (26.1247855, -97.9577671); straight back Lakeview Drive from entrance gate. Replacing tail feathers. Reddish undertail coverts. Berry residue on bill. Only the 3rd eBird record for the LRGV and 4th for Texas. Photos.
Photos taken

Bird observed flying to Pyracantha shrub below the picnic area at ~ 1600 hours.  Single male.  We observed the bird ~ 20 minutes while it feed on the Pyracantha fruit.  It primarily perched on a low plant limb approximatey 3 feet about the ground away from the Pyracantha shrub.  The bird was still there when we left.  Bird 10 - 12 inches in length.  Irridescent green on the back.  Long, narrow grayisn tail with thin terminal dark band.  Black facial mask.  Short, somewhat hooked, yellow bill.  Throat dark, upper breast greenish, whitish breast band and a pinkish red abdomen.

Seen and photographed by this observer at 2:51 PM about halfway up Panther Canyon, Landa Park.  Clearly, an Elegant Trogon, the dorsal region of the bird was a brownish gray with a long copper colored tail.  The throat was a dark gray and the chest and belly were a lighter gray with a white streak across the breast just below the throat.  The under-tail coverts were a rosy reddish color. The bill was a pale yellowish and the bird had a white streak behind the eye that was bordered on the rear with black.  The outer three graduated rectrices were black and white striped.  Observed in subdued afternoon sunlight to the rear of the observer shining on the bird.  Seen with 10X42 Swarovski binoculars.  I am familiar with this species having seen it many times while living in Costa Rica and on visits to SE AZ.

Observation Details: 1st sighting & call about 150 yds. up from S Fork Cave Creek Trailhead @ 06:00. Male was detected high in pine tree, calling several times. Poor photograph, but photo file shows GPS location GPS: 31.870,-109.187.  2nd ELTR opportunity was heard only at GPS: 31.863,-109.190 at the center spot of my assigned territory (above second crossing) across the creek on the south side. The call was that of a solitary male.  3rd ELTR was sighted & heard en route back to the S Fork Cave Creek trailhead about 11:30 am. Was seen defending a cavity nest on an adjacent dead Sycamore snag adjacent from where the male was calling. The ELTR was observed chasing off three different NOFL from the cavity hole when they approached it. Many obs. were taking photos. It was not determined if this individual was the same one reported several hours earlier at 06:00 closer to the trailhead. The third individual seen and photographed well (2) was seen at GPS: 31.869,-109.188. Phone photo, included, also showed same GPS location.

I was bringing my feeders back out after a rain storm when I saw a bird fly up to one of my feeders. It perched on the top of one of my woodpecker feeders. I noticed the white flared tail when it perched and thought it was a dove. As I got closer I noticed that it was squatter then a dove and had a thick yellow bill. I also noticed the white teardrop coming down from its eye. It had a darker, gray-green hood and lighter breast. It sat on the feeder pole for a minute or two while I took pictures. When I started to back away it flew across the street into the neighbors olive tree. I was able to see some red feathering in the center of the tail as it flew away. I think it was female due to the white teardrop and the relatively uniform back color. I'm not sure if it was a coppery-tailed or elegant.

It flew into a cottonwood and perched silently and still for a couple of minutes with its front toward me.  An apparent female or immature with a redish lower belly, a white line separating the dark breast from the gray upper belly, and a long squared-off tail with fine black-and-white bars and white tips. A lingering transient or rare winter visitor.

Parte superior y con lomo verde, vientre rojizo. Cola cuadrada con franjas contrastantes blancos - negros. Anillo en el ojo y pico, ambos color amarillo-naranja.

Se observo en una zona de matorral medianamente conservado. Parte superior verde esmeralda, cola cobriza, cara oscura sin ninguna otra seña particular y ojo con un anillo ocular rojizo. A diferencia del ejemplar visto en el parque Querétaro 2000, éste no presentó la línea blanca postocular, por lo que se considera qué se trata de individuos distintos. El pecho oscuro en la parte superior, seguido de una línea blanca sucia, en la zona del pecho medio y área ventral un gris con algunas zonas blanquecinas y finalmente rojo en la zona ventral más inferior. Por la ausencia de marcas faciales como la línea blanca postocular presente en los inmaduros y ausente en los adultos maduros, se consideró que el ejemplar era un macho adulto.

Male at nest. Lifer! Very suspenseful chase. Heard singing from quite a distance, then we slowly crept closer until it sounded like it was right above us. It continued to elude while we walked around the tree in silent confusion trying to see it. Finally michael spotted it in the nest, and I saw it briefly before it flew out and perched in the open in a conifer. It continued to sing as we watched it for several minutes, before finally flushing upstream. We waited at least half an hour for its return but it never did. Fantastic looks at a fantastic bird

Encountered three individuals approximately 100 meters south of the junction of the old trailhead and new trail.  Initially we did not notice the hatch year bird until reviewing the photographs.  In the photograph you can see the female on the left showing red on the belly and the hatch year on the right with a white belly.  The male was approximately 10 meters above the pair.  On the return hike, we encountered the male and female again but did not see the hatch year. The female flew over the trail and our heads and landed in a tree. We studied her for a bit then heard the male calling about 10 meters down the trail and were able to locate him very low to the ground.

Spectacular! Heard one softly chuckling on the north side of the culvert so we descended into the stream bed. Saw a male and female fly into a tree just up the slope but lost them. Waited to see if they would come out and were surprised to see two females fly up the slope and perch. Could see both females and hear the male calling at the same time. Females had a brown back, red belly, yellow bill, long tail hanging straight down. Never got a great look at the male other than seeing the dark green back in flight. Distant pics of females.

Two birds heard at 6:49, still calling at 7:17; approx. location 31.51184, -110.39021, up slope E of road. Presumed pair: one giving slow, higher pitched “koink koink”; the other giving fast, lower pitched “kow kow kow”. At 8:00, farther up canyon, possibly the same pair seen investigating cavity in dead oak W of road in main drainage. Female gave “kow kow kow” call and ate caterpillar while male was in cavity. Then the male emerged and perched while the female entered and stayed in cavity at least 7 minutes (we moved up canyon). At 10:00 on our return, the male was giving “kow kow kow” calls near the first cavity, then he entered another cavity in a different dead tree and continued calling (from inside the cavity, unseen) for 6-8 more minutes. Female not seen or heard. Down canyon about 0.25 mile a different male was seen and photographed and recorded at 10:30. Same male photographed again 0.4 mile downstream at 11:15.

Male trogon seen at 4:45 PM approximately one mile up the trail. The bird flew across the trail from the west to east about 100 feet past the entering national forest sign right where the trail makes the first switchback across the creek. He sat on a lower branch of a sycamore tree and then dropped down onto a three foot tree stump on the ground. He then briefly flew up and caught a large insect and went back into the lower part of the sycamore tree and ate it. I spent about five minutes with the bird before he flew north up the creek. I will attach photos of the trogon eating the insect and perched on the short tree stump.

Media notes: Elegant Trogons -two
Observation Details: Barb M. told us to take the trail 0.1mi up canyon from the amphitheater bridge.  Sure enough, I soon heard a distinctive 'bark'.  My ears are a bit wonky, but these birds always sound like they use a mechanical arf to communicate.  The two birds were in a tree just upslope from a rock fall.  I checked my Garmin.  It read 0.1mi.  Barb is good!  Thanks Barb.  Keith walked a short distance further to see if he could get a better picture.  About then, one Trogon flew off and the other came closer to us.  Gradually, it circled around us, stopping several times for photo ops.  By the time we returned to the car, it was waiting for us in the tree at the parking lot end of the bridge.

Observation Details: Please see attached photos.  Blue Jay sized, grayish bird with long, flat tail.  Stout, yellow bill.  Yellow eye ring.  White, horizontal line behind eye. Locality: Panther Canyon Nature Trail - Landa Park, New Braunfels
Observation Details: Found the previous weekend (1/27/18) but reported on Saturday night (2/3) after being properly identified; Hadn't seen a positive report all morning but decided to head down and search. Upon arriving, Eric Carpenter gave me the heads up that the bird had been refound and was being observed midway along the Panther Canyon Trail. Several folks helped us get on the bird, which was actively moving from tree to tree and primarily along the main creek wash.   The bird appeared to be a female with prominent white mark behind the eye, red orbital ring, and yellow bill. Grayish head and chest, which terminated abruptly, forming a white collar. Rosy belly and vent, grayish/green back, coppery central tail feathers, and unique barred undertail pattern.   It made its way up a steep wash on the side of the hill and wasn't seen again for over an hour, appearing around 5:23pm near the exact spot it was reported on Sunday evening. We observed the bird much longer and at a closer distance than earlier, but in much poorer lighting.
Bird was eye level at first then flew multiple times to different branches, was seen for about 10 minutes then flew up the hill. photos included

Media notes: Elegant Trogon, immature male, private yard, Portal, Cochise County,  AZ, November 24, 2021, Carol R. Comeau
Observation Details: Dodie Logue reported hearing and seeing an immature male trogon at 9:15 AM in the creek bed across from the Portal library annex. At 12:10 PM the bird was heard and seen calling on the hill above my house. The bird flew downhill back towards "downtown" Portal. There are many ripe pyracanthas around downtown Portal. So, if the bird has not left it may still be around downtown Portal. My last yard sighting of a trogon was August 15, 2005. That bird left the yard and flew south along the base of the mountains. Media notes: The bird chased down an insect.
Observation Details: Seen and photographed by this observer at 2:51 PM about halfway up Panther Canyon, Landa Park.  Clearly, an Elegant Trogon, the dorsal region of the bird was a brownish gray with a long copper colored tail.  The throat was a dark gray and the chest and belly were a lighter gray with a white streak across the breast just below the throat.  The under-tail coverts were a rosy reddish color. The bill was a pale yellowish and the bird had a white streak behind the eye that was bordered on the rear with black.  The outer three graduated rectrices were black and white striped.  Observed in subdued afternoon sunlight to the rear of the observer shining on the bird.  Seen with 10X42 Swarovski binoculars.  I am familiar with this species having seen it many times while living in Costa Rica and on visits to SE AZ.

Bird observed flying to Pyracantha shrub below the picnic area at ~ 1600 hours.  Single male.  We observed the bird ~ 20 minutes while it feed on the Pyracantha fruit.  It primarily perched on a low plant limb approximatey 3 feet about the ground away from the Pyracantha shrub.  The bird was still there when we left.  Bird 10 - 12 inches in length.  Irridescent green on the back.  Long, narrow grayisn tail with thin terminal dark band.  Black facial mask.  Short, somewhat hooked, yellow bill.  Throat dark, upper breast greenish, whitish breast band and a pinkish red abdomen.

Female. Heard first, giving a short sputtering call reminiscent of the Gray Tree Frog of the eastern US. Initial thought was that it might be a squirrel, but  subsequent iterations of the call were identical, and silence between them seemed to indicate not a squirrel. Then y-b cuckoo crossed my mind, since I'd seen one here a few days earlier, but zero response to playback of just the intro notes - kuk-kuk-kuk - of the typical cuckoo outburst had me baffled, until I dared consider a trogon. The bird still vocalizing after two minutes of these ruminations, I decided to risk a close approach to the large ornamental pear tree where the calls were coming from, peered up into it, and was delighted to see a female Elegant Trogon in unobscured, frontal view about ten feet up in the bare branches of the interior of the tree. We traded stares for about 5 seconds, upon which she bolted toward Miller Creek (dry) and I lost sight of her around the corner of the house. Camera in hand, I spotted her at the creekbed, perching between fluttering sallies, and managed one poor but diagnostic photo. As I angled for a better one showing the bird's head, which was annoyingly obscured by a branch, she slipped away and I did not see her again.

Media notes: My terrible image of front of bird showing dark head and bib, light belly and breast, pinkish-red under tail, and longish tail.
Observation Details: Please see attached photos.  Blue Jay sized, grayish bird with long, flat tail.  Stout, yellow bill.  Yellow eye ring.  White, horizontal line behind eye.  Pinkish-red under tail.  Black and white pattern on outer tail feathers.  About twenty five birders were present.  We saw the bird around 1:30 p.m., and watched it for at least 10 minutes.  Probably same bird present at this location for at least a week.  Thanks, Dennis Shepler, for posting today's sighting on Texbirds Facebook.

Seen and photographed by this observer at 2:51 PM about halfway up Panther Canyon, Landa Park.  Clearly, an Elegant Trogon, the dorsal region of the bird was a brownish gray with a long copper colored tail.  The throat was a dark gray and the chest and belly were a lighter gray with a white streak across the breast just below the throat.  The under-tail coverts were a rosy reddish color. The bill was a pale yellowish and the bird had a white streak behind the eye that was bordered on the rear with black.  The outer three graduated rectrices were black and white striped.  Observed in subdued afternoon sunlight to the rear of the observer shining on the bird.  Seen with 10X42 Swarovski binoculars.  I am familiar with this species having seen it many times while living in Costa Rica and on visits to SE AZ.

Stunning ad. male, seen pretty far up the canyon (have GPS point saved). Perched in full sun on a dead snag, gorgeous. Sadly, after only a few moments a hummingbird sp. zoomed over and chased this poor dude straight up the canyon wall through some stunted, gnarly oaks. Upper breast, crown, nape emerald green; face dark with vibrant yellow-orange eyering; large yellow bill; upper breast separated from crimson lower breast, belly, and under tail by crisp white band; long white tail (under)  with fine, subtle grayish barring/streaks and tipped by a black band. Saw what I assume is the same bird much lower on the way down and was able to get this Lochness monster-esque but nonetheless diagnostic photo through my bins.

Female seen in ditch west of Grebe Marsh Alligator pond.  Was flying north (towards us) in front of/had been flushed by 2 other birders who were down the trail from us. Banked in front of me and behind Marla. Initial sighting 25m from me, about 5 m from Marla. Bright red vent fading to pink mid belly and whitish forward of that.  Long tail brown on top.  Graduated outer tail feathers with each retrix shorter and with white tips.  Making chattering alarm call in flight.  Perched in brush somewhere between us and other birders, then flushed and flew down brushline silhouetted against sun.  Perched in brush near us briefly before flushing again. Showed characteristic undulating flight pattern as she flew away from us down ditch.  Was in clear view for 2 undulations, perhaps 50m before swooping up to perch in mesquite overhanging ditch.  Every time she perched was obscured by brush, hence no photographs.  After flushing once more, flew across road and across Grebe Marsh and disappeared.  Could hear chattering between Grebe and Alligator Pond.  I've probably seen 15+ ELTR this year (in AZ) and I'm 100% certain of the ID.  @~1610hrs.  Added sketches drawn solely from memory w/o consulting field guide.  2 sketches of bird banking away as first observed. 1 sketch of bird flying directly away down ditch.

Se observó un individuo con parte superior del cuerpo verde esmeralda y cola cobriza ambos iridiscentes, el extremo de la cla bordeado en negro, en ocasiones se dejaban ver algunas recteices exteriores blancas sobresaliendo de las centrales de color cobre. Estas caracteristicas inicales corresponden con T. elegans, en un principio se pensó que se trataba de una hembra, ya que la cabeza tenia la característica marca blanca detrás del ojo así como un anillo ocular rojizo. La parte superior del pecho con la coloración oscura y posteriormente una línea blanca sucia, seguida de un color café grisáceo y después rojo mezclado con blanco en la parte inferior. Posteriormente se realizó una búsqueda de imágenes para confirmar el sexo del ave y se encontró que los machos inmaduros presentan estas características. De manera clásica se menciona que la hembra es completamente café en la parte superior sin ninguna coloracion verde, la cola cobriza, la marca blanca detrás del ojo y la parte inferior con las características ya mencionadas, sin embargo, el individuo observado presentaba la parte superior del cuerpo completamente verde brillante además de los otros rasgos ya mencionados, por lo que se concluyó que se trataba de un macho inmaduro de esta especie. El ave se encontraba con sus plumas en buen estado, sin mostrar el desgaste característico de los ejemplares escapados y con  plena capacidad de vuelo, se le vio cazando exitosamente insectos en vuelo. Aunque fue posible observarlo con cierta cercanía, se mostró tímido y cambiaba de percha al más mínimo movimiento percibido.

Locality: Garden Canyon Rd--BETWEEN Upper Picnic Area and Sawmill Canyon
Media notes: Worst trogon photo ever.
Observation Details: Flew across the road at alligator juniper grove just below Sawmill Canyon parking area, then moved along to the parking area, various flights and repositions. We had great views, but impossible to get a photo through the branches (worst trogon photo ever). Also it was making the "fast chuckle" call occasionally, an alarm call, which Pieplow's guide says is infrequent. Audio and very poor photo attached. At first I thought it was a female based on the red only being on the belly (I would have expected males to stay on territory this late into the winter). But after talking to Theresa Lawson who saw an ELTR male with partial red belly in Ramsey the next day, and reading Birds of the World plumage account, mine is likely a first-winter male also. BoW says the male has a breast like a female, may or may not be mixed with red. But I didn’t see the back so I re-examined my horrible photos and a couple show light gray by the upper wing, that would make it a male. So changing this to likely first-year male.

Observed along stream below Santa Rita Lodge. Vocalizing and flying from tree to tree.

Media notes: Pyracantha fruit.
Observation Details: Bird observed flying to Pyracantha shrub below the picnic area at ~ 1600 hours.  Single male.  We observed the bird ~ 20 minutes while it feed on the Pyracantha fruit.  It primarily perched on a low plant limb approximatey 3 feet about the ground away from the Pyracantha shrub.  The bird was still there when we left.  Bird 10 - 12 inches in length.  Irridescent green on the back.  Long, narrow grayisn tail with thin terminal dark band.  Black facial mask.  Short, somewhat hooked, yellow bill.  Throat dark, upper breast greenish, whitish breast band and a pinkish red abdomen.
Characteristic "arf arf" call heard. Seen through the trees
