Locality: stakeout Elegant Trogon, N Pier Mountain Rd (2025)
Observation Details: ***rare. Found by MW on Friday and CM on Saturday in their back yards, today it was perched in the front yards along the street. Seen by several of the residents of the west side of the street in their back yards overlooking the wash. Visitors welcome to park along N Pier Mountain Rd. and walk, checking the larger trees, but the bird evidently moves around a lot and spends most of the days in parts unknown; evening seems to be when most sightings occur. At least three lowland sightings from the Tucson area: Sweetwater (Jun 2008), west Tucson (July 2021), central Tucson (Dec 2023) plus a few others.

I only saw this Trogon as it was perched facing away from me so that I could only see the plumage from the back. It was mostly emerald green with a fairly long tail that had paler green colouring than the back. The head was also green with a yellow bill. The flanks looked grey with the fine markings and the feathering seemed to fold over towards the back and covering some of the wing. The outer edge of the tail had fine black and white lines.

Sky Islands Traverse, San Simon, Arizona, US (31.863, -109.19)
Observation Details: 1st sighting & call about 150 yds. up from S Fork Cave Creek Trailhead @ 06:00. Male was detected high in pine tree, calling several times. Poor photograph, but photo file shows GPS location GPS: 31.870,-109.187.  2nd ELTR opportunity was heard only at GPS: 31.863,-109.190 at the center spot of my assigned territory (above second crossing) across the creek on the south side. The call was that of a solitary male.  3rd ELTR was sighted & heard en route back to the S Fork Cave Creek trailhead about 11:30 am. Was seen defending a cavity nest on an adjacent dead Sycamore snag adjacent from where the male was calling. The ELTR was observed chasing off three different NOFL from the cavity hole when they approached it. Many obs. were taking photos. It was not determined if this individual was the same one reported several hours earlier at 06:00 closer to the trailhead. The third individual seen and photographed well (2) was seen at GPS: 31.869,-109.188. Phone photo, included, also showed same GPS location.
Two males barking, one seen very well!
Two males barking, one seen very well!

Locality: Parque Estatal Sierra de Guadalupe--Charca de La Mora
Observation Details: Observamos dos machos adultos, increíble; ambos perchado en sitios relativamente contiguos y permaneciendo relativamente juntos cuando se movian de árbol en árbol; algunos estudios de campo indican que esta especie forma parejas de machos en sitios de reproducción para cortejar a la hembra aproximadamente entre marzo y abril (Bent 1940) algo increíble debido a que para el Valle de México es la primera vez se da este evento de invasión de la especie o al menos en tiempos históricos recientes. Before I cared about birds I had a bright adult male perch right on top of me. I was looking for flies around Madera creek a few hundred yards below the picnic area, heard a strange croaking, realized it must be a bird and so looked up, and noticed this fine fellow perching a couple meters above me! Watched him for a few minutes and snapped some pics with my cell phone. Didn’t realize what I’d actually seen for a few hours, when I eventually came across an info notice in the parking lot about the trogons and put two and two together. Photos, also shared here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/80137411

Observation Details: 13:30 - This is a female. Not sure if it's the mate of the one being seen here, but still cool to see. She was chattering like crazy too. I was bringing my feeders back out after a rain storm when I saw a bird fly up to one of my feeders. It perched on the top of one of my woodpecker feeders. I noticed the white flared tail when it perched and thought it was a dove. As I got closer I noticed that it was squatter then a dove and had a thick yellow bill. I also noticed the white teardrop coming down from its eye. It had a darker, gray-green hood and lighter breast. It sat on the feeder pole for a minute or two while I took pictures. When I started to back away it flew across the street into the neighbors olive tree. I was able to see some red feathering in the center of the tail as it flew away. I think it was female due to the white teardrop and the relatively uniform back color. I'm not sure if it was a coppery-tailed or elegant.

Found around 3 P.M. by David Mills, and refound here: 33.381483,-112.373445, at 4:40 P.M.  Once refound at these cords, the Trogon went further east along mesquites lining the south side of Casey Abbott Road before flying to the north side of Casey Abbott and going to where David first had it in the general area of: 33.382671,-112.370357.  The Trogon favored mesquites for the most part, where it may be feeding on berries in the mistletoe.  Bird flew around a lot and seemed a little skittish at times, but it never flew long distances.  Perched on a sign at one point.  The last time we saw it it went back south again into mesquites south of Casey Abbott.  This appears to be the 5th record for Maricopa County, an outstanding discovery by David.

Observation Details: Two Trogons calling together on opposite sides of slot canyon at 6,600ft elevation, separated by approximately 30-to-50 yards. Male was flying up and down the creek calling, mostly mornings and late afternoons. On Saturday we saw it clinging to a sycamore trunk, then putting its head into a woodpecker hole. Eventually it went completely inside for a while. When it came out half a dozen Acorn Woodpeckers were mobbing it. It sat perfectly quiet on a small branch just below the hole, looking as serene as owls can be when mobbed. After 15 or 20 minutes of this, it suddenly and with surprising speed for a Trogon dived on one of the Woodpeckers. When that happened all the woodpeckers split.
